@node "Intro" "Introduction"

Welcome to QWKDoor!

QWKDoor is a program that generates @{"QWK" link g_QWK} mail bundles. It is used on a BBS
to to let the users download all unread messages so that they can read them
without having to worry about the phonebill. The users can use programs such
as AmiQWK and Q-Blue (Amiga) or BlueWave (MS-DOS) to comfortably read the
mail and write replies that are uploaded to the BBS later.

QWKDoor uses the UMS messagebase. If your BBS program doesn't support UMS,
you will have to have two messagebases or get another QWK-door.

In the archive you should find a file called QWK_User.doc. It is a manual
that describes how to use the program as a user. It might be a good idea
to make it available for download. It contains lots of important
information, so it is a good idea for the sysop to read it too.

Features of QWKDoor:

 o QWKDoor can split large messages into messages with a maximum number
   or lines that can be configured by the sysop and you can set a maximum
   number of messages in each bundle. These features are added because
   some readers can't handle long messages or too large bundles.

 o QWKDoor supports different charsets

 o Message size, number of charsets and number of archives are only
   limited by the amount of free memory.

 o Replies in one area can be automatically moved to an other area.

 o QWKDoor can be configured not to allow replies in certain areas

 o For each area there are different security levels for reading and
   writing messages.

 o You can allow a single user to read/write in an area that he normally
   wouldn't be able to read. You can also prevent a user from reading
   in an area, for example if he has been thrown out by the moderator.

 o You can add, drop and reset areas from the offline reader if it
   supports it.

 o QWKDoor handles mail to other systems without any problems.

 o QWKDoor works when running a multi-line BBS

 o Hello, News and Goodbye files supported

 o QWKDoor can use a standard @{".newsrc" link g_newsrc} file

@endnode

@node "Install"

The installation consists of three parts:

 1) Make a new directory for QWKDoor and copy QWKDoor.prefs and QWKDoor
    there.

 2) Edit QWKDoor.prefs (see @{"Configuration" link Config})

 3) Change your BBS configuration

@endnode

@node "Config" "Configuration"

This part describes all the configuration keywords you can have in
QWKDoor.prefs. Please read this section carefully, otherwise you might
miss some useful options.

See QWKDoor.prefs for a sample configuration.

   BBSName
   =======
   This is the name of your BBS. It is later written to the CONTROL.DAT
   file.


   BBSProgram
   ==========
   Name and version of your BBS program. Example: "KMS 1.75"


   BBSID
   =====
   The ID of your BBS. This ID should be unique for your BBS. Mail bundles
   will be called <BBSID>.QWK. This is limited to eight characters due to
   the 8+3 limit on most MS-DOS computers.


   City
   ====
   The city of the BBS. Max length: 40 characters


   Phone
   =====
   The phone number of the BBS.


   Sysop
   =====
   The name of the sysop.


   Hello
   =====
   Name and path of your Hello file. You could use this file to remind
   the users of that they shouldn't quote too much or something similar.
   Max length: 80 characters


   Goodbye
   =======
   Name and path of your Goodbye file.


   News
   ====
   Name and path of your News file. This file is only included in the
   archive if it has been changed since the last time the user
   successfully downloaded a mail bundle.


   Datafile
   ========
   This is the data file used by QWKDoor to save the numbers of the
   conferences. Default: "PROGDIR:QWKDoor.data"


   Download
   ========
   The command that is executed when a bundle should be sent to the
   users. You can use these special characters here:

   %u   Username
   %d   User directory
   %1   Whatever was specified as ARG1 on the command line
   %2   Whatever was specified as ARG2 on the command line
   %3   Whatever was specified as ARG3 on the command line
   %f   File when downloading, directory when uploading


   Upload
   ======
   The same as Download, but is executed when QWKDoor expects a reply
   packet to be uploaded to the BBS.


   Tempdir
   =======
   The temporary directory where QWKDoor creates the mail bundle. QWKDoor
   creates a new directory called QWK_<username> in this directory to avoid
   problems when several users are downloading QWK bundles at the same time
   on a multiline BBS.


   Split
   =====
   This is the maximum number of lines in a message. If a message is
   larger, it will be splitted into several smaller messages.
   Default: 200 lines


   MaxTexts
   ========
   This is the maximum number of messages in one bundle.
   Default: 500 messages


   Area
   ====
   With this keyword, you configure the areas that you want to make
   available for your users.

   Syntax: Area <group>|MAIL <desc> <read> <write> <reply>|NOREPLY

   Group: This is the UMS group of this area or "MAIL". If you enter
          "MAIL", this area will be used for private messages.

          Example: fidonet.AMY_POINT

   Desc:  The description of the area. Try to make this short since
          the QWK standard doesn't allow area names longer than 13
          characters.

          Example: Amy_Point

   Read:  The security level needed to read in the area

   Write: The security level needed to write in the area

   Reply: (Optional) All replies written in this area will be
          redirected to the area specified here. You can also specify
          "NOREPLY" if you don't want to allow replies in this area.

   Examples:

   Area fidonet.AMY_POINT "Amy_Point"   10   10
   Area fidonet.INFO      "Info"        10  255
   Area fidonet.JOKES     "Jokes"       10   10 NOREPLY
   Area fidonet.ANNOUNCE  "Announce"    10   10 fidonet.SOFTWARE
   Area fidonet.SOFTWARE  "Software"    10   10


   Organization
   ============
   Use this to set the Organization for one or more areas. (Organization
   lines are converted to Origins for FidoNet echos by FidoExport)

   Syntax: <Pattern> <organization>

   Pattern: The name of a _group_ or a pattern.

   Organization: The organization for these areas

   Examples:

   Organization fidonet.#? "QWK in FidoNet"
   Organization #?         "Default QWK"     ; Used for all other areas


   Charset
   =======
   With this keyword, you specify the charsets that you want to let your
   users select. If you don't enter any charsets, character translation
   will be turned off.

   Syntax: Charset <name> <file>

   Name: The name of the charset

         Examples: "Latin-1", "IBMPC", "Macintosh"

   File: The file where the charset is described. QWKDoor uses the same
         format as KMS for the charsets, so if you are running that BBS
         program, you can use those files directly. Files for Latin-1
         (Amiga) and IBM-PC are included in the archive.


   Archiver
   ========
   Here you can spcify the archivers your users can select from.

   Syntax: Archiver <name> <unpack command> <pack command>

   Name:           The name of the archiver. Example: "Zip"

   Unpack command: The command used to unpack bundles

   Pack command:   The command used to pack bundles

   In the commands, you can use the following special codes:

   %a   archive
   %d   directory

   Examples:

   Archiver "LhA"                  "SYS:Packers/LhA x \"%a\"" "SYS:Packers/LhA a \"%a\" \"%d/#?\""
   Archiver "LhA - no compression" "SYS:Packers/LhA x \"%a\"" "SYS:Packers/LhA -z a \"%a\" \"%d/#?\""
   Archiver "Zip"                  "SYS:Packers/UnZip \"%a\"" "SYS:Packers/Zip \"%a\" \"%d/*\""


   User
   ====
   This is used to give a single user special rights in conferences. He/she
   can be given access to special areas or forbidden to enter other areas.

   This overrides the security levels specified for the area.

   Syntax: User <username> <group> NOREAD/READ/WRITE/NOWRITE

   Username: The name of the users that is given specieal rights

   Group:    Name of the _group_

   NOREAD:   The user is not allowed to read in this area

   READ:     The user is allowed to read in this area

   NOWRITE:  The user is not allowed to write in this area

   WRITE:    The user is allowed to write in this area

   Examples:

   User "Johan Billing" fidonet.SYSOP READ WRITE
   User "Stupid User"   fidonet.SOFTWARE NOREAD NOWRITE
@endnode

@node "Integration" "Integration"

This is the most tricky part of setting up QWKDoor. If you use KMS, you
can use the ARexx scripts included in this archive, otherwise read the
"Other" section for some hints.

   @{"KMS  " link "KMS"}
   @{"Other" link "Other"}

If you have managed to setup QWKDoor for your BBS, please send me the
scripts so that I can include them in the next version of QWKDoor.
@endnode

@node "KMS"

1) Copy QWK.KMS to KMS:Rexx/

2) Add QWK as a command to KMS:Data/KMS_COMMANDS.DAT

3) Enter the following commands for upload and download in QWKDoor.prefs:

   Download "rx KMS:QWKDoor/Download.rexx \"%f\" %1"
   Upload   "rx KMS:QWKDoor/Upload.rexx \"%f\" %1"

   (Change the paths if you need to. Please check the paths in the ARexx
   scripts too...)

Finished!
@endnode

@node "Other"

So, this is a bit tricky. In most cases this requires knowledge of ARexx
and/or AmigaDOS scripts, so probably only experienced sysops will manage
to do this.

A few hints:

 o Use the ARG1 option on command line to specify the node number
   the user is on. Then use %1 to pass this to the Upload/Download
   scripts which perform the transfer. This way will probably work
   with most BBS systems.

 o If your BBS system can't start transfers when running a door,
   you can use a external program to transfer the files. There is
   a number of such programs, for example rz, sz, XPRD and XPR-Gate.
   (Don't forget to set serial.device to shared mode!)

 o If that doesn't work either, things get a bit harder, but not
   impossible. You could make a File-Attach to the user or put the
   bundle in a private filearea.

 o If you want to have an own fancy menu for the different options
   in QWKDoor, you can use to GOTO switch to skip the main menu and
   directly go to a specific part of QWKDoor.
@endnode

@node "Command" "Command line"

 NAME/A,PASSWORD/A,LEVEL/A/N,USERDIR/A,SERVER/K,GOTO/K,SETTINGS/K,
 NEWSRC/K,NOASK/S,NOPROGRESS/S,ARG1/K,ARG2/K,ARG3/K:

 NAME:       The name of the user

 PASSWORD:   The password of the user in your ums.config.

 LEVEL:      The security level of the user. The level decides which areas
             the user is allowed to read and write in. A user with level
             255 is the sysop.

 USERDIR:    The directory where the configuration file of the user is
             saved. The file is called QWK_<username>, so if your BBS
             program doesn't have a directory for each user, you can put
             all configurations in one directory.

 SERVER:     The UMS message base that should be used. Default: "default"

 GOTO:       Use this to skip the main menu and directly go to one of the
             parts of the program. Valid parts are: Download, Upload,
             Tag, Settings and EditUnread. This is good if you want to
             make your own fancy menu. :-)

 SETTINGS:   Use this settings file instead of "PROGDIR:QWKDoor.prefs"

 NEWSRC:     QWKDoor can use a standard @{".newsrc" link g_newsrc} file to save what areas
             have been tagged. Pass the name of this file here.

 NOASK:      If you use this switch, QWKDoor will never stop the uploading
             or downloading of messages to ask the user for something.

 NOPROGRESS: Turns off the %-indicator when downloading messages.

 ARG1-3:    The strings specified here can be passed to the download and
            upload commands with %1-3. Use this for node number, device
            and unit or similar.

@endnode

